Someone told me when he was a child he found a water fountain in the middle of a forest, but when he went back later it was gone. Then just a few weeks ago his priest sent him to check some land he was buying for a new Orthodox mission and it was that exact area with the fountain

... where he said he wished to build a water fountain in the middle of the forest for the wild birds to drink from and refresh themselves in during summer days. Joy, jubilation, etc. And ofc. falling water generates massive amounts of negative ions, all alt-health guys will know.

Rene Guenon wrote that the "Earthly Paradise" contains four fountains of water (analogical to the four rivers of Eden) so the symbolism is quite apt for such spot marked as sacred. It also recalls one quote of either St. Amphilochios or St. Porphyrios (someone will remind me) ...

One of the most beautiful thoughts in von Leibniz's Theodicy is him saying already in the preface that there is "nothing so agreeable as loving that which is worthy of love". It represents the total ordering of the cosmos, rearranging the entirety of creation in the proper way.

I think if you take a page from Eriugena you must conclude that this goes one step further and you can *only* love what is worthy of love. Thus if you love something, it must be worthy of love in some way. And I am getting reports from a source that there is nothing so agreeable.
